            <div id="Rapport">
                <div>
                    <p><strong>Questions that you can ask about the asset</strong></p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Is there a particular reason why you are looking for this car? </li>
                        <li>How much research have you completed? </li>
                        <li>Are you set on this make and model or are you open to look at other vehicles? </li>
                        <li>Is the car for family? For yourself? How will you be using it?</li>
                    </ol>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <p><br></br>People/prospects are in the market to buy a car, bike etc. This is a very large and exciting purchase. Talk about the car, connect 
                with the customer. This is where the emotion comes into the sales process.</p>    
        		</div>
                <div>
                    <p><strong>Job and Career questions</strong></p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>So, tell me how you got into this line of work?</li>
                        <li>Do you enjoy it?</li>
                        <li>Did you study to get into this field?</li>
                        <li>What are your long-term job and career goals?</li>
                    </ol>
                </div>
        		<div>
            		<p><br></br>Most people are usually working in their particular job or industry because they have worked very hard to get their either through study or persistence, most people do what they do because they enjoy the work, are good at etc. Talk about that and connect. </p>    
				</div>
                <div>
                    <p><strong>Locality questions or statements</strong></p>  
                    <p>Savvy customers reside across Australia, from all major capital cities to regional Australia. You must as a consultant have a general idea about where your customers reside and over time develop your knowledge on cities and towns across Australia and their major attractions. Trying to find a connection with a prospect around where they live build massive amount of credibility, personalises the relationship and knowing little bits of information about their backyard will allow you to develop a great connection with the customer. Knowledge will come with experience but you can start off with some basic statements such as:  <strong>Sydney lead </strong>? talk about the fact we have an office in Crows Nest.  <strong>Adelaide lead</strong>? talk about the fact we have out head office in Adelaide, Norwood. </p>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <p><strong>Questions for Business Customers </strong></p> 
                    <ol>
                        <li>So, tell me how has business been this year? Better than last?</li>
                        <li>What?s your plan for next 12 months of trading, any big deals/contracts coming through? </li>
                        <li>How did you end up in this line of work?</li>
                        <li>What kind of products do you sell, is it easy to bring in business?	</li>
                    </ol>
                </div>
                <div> 
                    <p><br></br>Business owners love to talk about their business, they spend so much time and sacrifice so much to be in business and hence love talking about their company, what they are doing today and what they are looking to achieve in the future. Use that! </p>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <p><strong>General rapport building questions</strong></p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>How was your weekend? </li>
                        <li>What do you do for fun?  </li>
                        <li>Talk about favorite sport, team, whatever it may be?</li>
                        <li>General news?</li>
                        <li>Personal interests - Family, partner, interest, hobbies. </li>
                        <li>Where did you vacation? </li>
                        <li>Where his kids go to school</li>
                    </ol>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <p><br></br><strong>To build you also need to: </strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Always be extremely nice, caring and have energy in your voice.</li>
                        <li>Stay POSITIVE in every instance.</li>
                        <li>Display huge amounts of enthusiasm about your product, yourself, your job and the organisation. </li>
                        <li>Talk about what achievements the company has accomplished, how big the company is. </li>
                        <li>Talk about yourself, your experiences, your family, your friends, your hobbies, cars that you like, car that you drive, what you did on the weekend?.and what you?re doing this weekend?. </li>
                        <li>Talk to customers about anything. People like to know that they are dealing with a human being and not just someone who wants to sell them something.</li>
                        <li>Show your personality, have a joke and really have fun on the phones. Have fun and don?t be afraid to be human, open up, if they don?t talk much, then you must. If they are big talkers, let them talk?. but make sure you still control the call!  </li>
                        <li>Don?t be afraid to have a sense of humour, you don?t need to be to formal always, know who you are speaking to and adapt.  </li>
                        <li>Find similarities with your customers, try and find one thing in common with every customer you deal with. You will be surprised how similar all of us are.   </li>
                        <li>The client must LIKE you. If the customer really likes you they will allow you to re-quote and WIN the business. This will only happen if you have a good relationship with your customer, this relationship can only happen through phone time ? through MEANINGFUL conversations!! A 5-minute convo consisting of just repayment and finance details will not cut it. PHONE TIME is so important. Take the time to get to know the person you are speaking to. </li>
                        <li>Find a CONNECTION </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <p><br></br>You will find that although we are all very different (people) there is usually some sort of a connection you can make with a person through some common interests and that?s what rapport building is all about! </p>
                </div>
		</div>
